<div id="review_3226367203" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3226367203" />
    <a title="The Cats’ Mother" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5720552-the-cats-mother"><img alt="The Cats’ Mother" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1640916118p2/5720552.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3226367203?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="The Cats’ Mother" class="user" itemprop="url" name="The Cats’ Mother" href="/user/show/5720552-the-cats-mother">The Cats’ Mother</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=x-read-in-2020">x-read-in-2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=x-2020-ebooks">x-2020-ebooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=action-or-suspense-thrillers">action-or-suspense-thrillers</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=bought-e-or-a-books-read">bought-e-or-a-books-read</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5720552-the-cats-mother?shelf=sci-fi-or-fantasy">sci-fi-or-fantasy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3226367203" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12054901007074713051">Bone Music is the start of the Burning Girl series, which I bought because I have an ARC of book three, Blood Victory, which comes out next month, and I can’t bear to read series out of order. I had assumed it was a trilogy but the blurb for that one doesn’t indicate it’s the end so happily it seems I have a new longer series to look forward to. I like genre mash-ups, and this crosses vigilante action thriller with a dose of light sci-fi/superhero to produce a character reminiscent of Marvel’s J</span>
  <span id="freeText12054901007074713051" style="display:none">Bone Music is the start of the Burning Girl series, which I bought because I have an ARC of book three, Blood Victory, which comes out next month, and I can’t bear to read series out of order. I had assumed it was a trilogy but the blurb for that one doesn’t indicate it’s the end so happily it seems I have a new longer series to look forward to. I like genre mash-ups, and this crosses vigilante action thriller with a dose of light sci-fi/superhero to produce a character reminiscent of Marvel’s Jessica Jones, but more likeable.<br /><br />Charlotte Rowe lives alone in the Arizona desert, trying to come to terms with her past: as a baby she was abducted by a serial killer couple who murdered her mother and hoped to raise her in their image. Rescued at age seven, she was then exploited by her birth father to make a series of gratuitous books and movies which created a sick following of crazies who know her as The Burning Girl. Having emancipated herself at sixteen, she finally found peace with her grandmother Luanne, who then died, leaving her bereft and alone. A therapist has been helping her, and persuades her to take a new drug to help ease her fears, but it does much more than that, giving her super-strength and rapid healing. These abilities attract the attention of a powerful corporation who want to use her for their own ends, but Charley is tired of being used by others...<br /><br />Christopher Rice is the son of Anne Rice, whose vampire novels kept me spellbound in the nineties. He has inherited her writing and storytelling talent, but fortunately not the overly flowery style and religious leanings that made me give up on her years ago. This starts well and manages to convey quite a lot of background without slowing the pace. This kind of story doesn’t need a lot of scene-setting and physical description of characters - and I liked that the main cast are not all good or all bad (even the serial killer Charley goes after evokes some sympathy - albeit not for long!) There’s a tiny touch of romance but I loved that Luke was not her teenage crush, but rather the bully who tormented her at school, so their relationship takes some time to evolve. <br /><br />This had plenty of action, and an interesting plot - obviously the outcome wasn’t really in any doubt but the motivations of some of the characters were not clear and a large part of the intrigue was figuring out what they were up to, and there’s a nice twist I didn’t see coming. There’s some violence, but the most gruesome parts happen off-screen and so most of what we see is bad guys getting what they deserve, which was very satisfying - I do like principled female vigilantes! The ending leaves things open for the next book, which I’ll be buying very soon. 4.5 rounded down for the present tense narration.<br />Oh an PS this line: “It’s a long flight, SFO to Atlanta. About four hours.” had me snorting - the author has clearly not travelled Down Under if he thinks that’s a long flight!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="12054901007074713051" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


